Mike, why is Joe wearing a tie?

13:25.644 --> 13:27.311
Because, technically,

13:27.312 --> 13:29.947
he's the boss of our new endeavor.

13:29.948 --> 13:33.017
Why is it a Christmas tie?

13:33.018 --> 13:34.952
He's probably just got the one,

13:34.953 --> 13:38.222
and he wants to make sure
everybody knows who's in charge.

13:38.223 --> 13:39.724
Ah, leadership.

13:39.725 --> 13:41.159
Yeah, it's a heady cocktail.

13:41.160 --> 13:43.394
Long hours, lazy workers, huh?

13:43.395 --> 13:44.395
(CHUCKLES)

13:44.396 --> 13:47.065
I miss it.

13:47.066 --> 13:48.900
I just want to work on cars, right?

13:48.901 --> 13:50.902
I don't want to take orders from Joe.

13:50.903 --> 13:53.671
I'm not one of his cats.

13:53.672 --> 13:55.573
You know, when you're the boss,

13:55.574 --> 13:56.908
Joe's a pain in your ass,

13:56.909 --> 13:59.544
so why don't you return the favor?

13:59.545 --> 14:01.345
Well, how would that help anybody?

14:01.346 --> 14:04.215
Well, you like to annoy people, right?

14:05.818 --> 14:07.385
Sure. Who doesn't?

14:08.420 --> 14:10.088
The nice.

14:10.089 --> 14:11.522
And since you're not,

14:11.523 --> 14:14.659
this might be a good way to
put the fun back into this.

14:14.660 --> 14:16.894
I like it.

14:16.895 --> 14:19.330
It's better than my murder
plan. (SHORT CHUCKLE)

14:19.331 --> 14:21.432
- That requires an alibi.
- Well...

14:21.433 --> 14:23.365
This a good time for a meeting, Baxter?

14:23.366 --> 14:25.768
Doesn't matter. A good time
is when the boss says it is.

14:25.769 --> 14:28.003
And, right now, he ain't the boss.

14:29.039 --> 14:30.539
Happy holidays.

14:32.042 --> 14:34.043
Sure, a good time for a
meeting. This is great.

14:34.044 --> 14:35.778
I'm here to serve, boss.

14:35.779 --> 14:38.047
Oh. Well, you got a new attitude.

14:38.048 --> 14:40.783
That's scary.

14:40.784 --> 14:43.218
Now, I looked up how to
start a business, okay?

14:43.219 --> 14:44.420
And we need a website

14:44.421 --> 14:46.021
- and a license.
- Whoa.

14:46.022 --> 14:48.023
That's a... that's a
lot of business jargon.

14:48.024 --> 14:50.292
Can you dumb that down a little bit?

14:50.293 --> 14:52.394
Well, there's a lot to do. Uh, Chuck,

14:52.395 --> 14:54.396
- you're in computers...
- You just said "urine".

14:54.397 --> 14:56.265
(CHUCKLES) He said "urine".

14:56.266 --> 14:57.600
Can we cut the chitchat?

14:57.601 --> 14:59.117
I'm trying to run a meeting here.

14:59.118 --> 15:01.036
Well, I guess I could take
a crack at the website.

15:01.037 --> 15:02.605
You just said "crack". (LAUGHS)

15:06.476 --> 15:08.644
If you're looking for cocktail onions,

15:08.645 --> 15:10.145
- they're in the pantry.
- (GROANS)

15:10.146 --> 15:13.048
Don't even say those words to me.

15:13.049 --> 15:15.451
We went to three stores
to find the kind you like.

15:15.452 --> 15:16.952
We thought you had a craving.

15:16.953 --> 15:18.053
That was then.

15:18.054 --> 15:20.723
Today, I'm feeling a brick of feta.

15:21.745 --> 15:23.069
You broke my husband.

15:23.070 --> 15:25.060
Oh, Mandy, you know what,
you were tricking him.

15:25.061 --> 15:26.261
It's not healthy.

15:26.262 --> 15:29.732
Screw healthy. We were happy.

15:29.733 --> 15:31.834
That's because Kyle is always happy.

15:31.835 --> 15:34.103
Yeah, well, that's one of
the reasons I married him.

15:34.104 --> 15:37.106
I don't have to work to make him happy.

15:37.107 --> 15:39.074
He came that way.

15:41.511 --> 15:43.245
Are you eating olives and whipped cream?

15:43.246 --> 15:44.813
What am I supposed to do?

15:44.814 --> 15:46.582
There's no feta!

15:48.818 --> 15:51.153
Anyway, thanks a lot, Mom.

15:51.154 --> 15:52.755
Now I have to do my laundry,

15:52.756 --> 15:54.957
and some slob left
it all over the floor.

15:56.793 --> 15:58.961
Mandy, remember I told you

15:58.962 --> 16:00.863
my parents had a chore list also?

16:00.864 --> 16:02.831
Yeah, yeah. That's
because, in every culture,

16:02.832 --> 16:05.720
marriage is about work and
shared responsibilities.

16:05.721 --> 16:07.512
I mean, that's-that's
what you were gonna say.

16:07.513 --> 16:08.671
Right, Jen?

16:08.672 --> 16:10.639
No.

16:12.108 --> 16:13.842
My mother loved flowers.

16:13.843 --> 16:15.611
She grew roses in her garden.

16:15.612 --> 16:17.846
And even though my father
didn't care about flowers,

16:17.847 --> 16:19.448
he had to prune them and clip one

16:19.449 --> 16:21.283
for the dinner table every night.

16:22.519 --> 16:23.952
After my mother died,

16:23.953 --> 16:26.622
my father continued
to maintain her garden.

16:26.623 --> 16:30.125
So I asked him why he
still did this chore.

16:30.126 --> 16:31.293
And he said,

16:31.294 --> 16:33.195
"It was never a chore.

16:33.196 --> 16:35.297
It was my gift to your mother.

16:35.298 --> 16:37.900
And now that she's gone, I
can still give her this gift.

16:37.901 --> 16:40.335
It keeps her close to me".

16:43.339 --> 16:44.907
I know I'm really hormonal,

16:44.908 --> 16:47.643
but we're all about to
burst into tears, right?

16:48.878 --> 16:50.312
That was beautiful.

16:50.313 --> 16:51.714
Oh, my God.

16:51.715 --> 16:53.882
I'm gonna go home and give Kyle the gift

16:53.883 --> 16:56.185
of actually doing my chores.

16:58.421 --> 17:01.090
(SIGHS) S-So, Jen,

17:01.091 --> 17:02.424
when you do chores for me,

17:02.425 --> 17:04.393
do you consider it a gift?

17:05.762 --> 17:07.496
Guess we'll find out when you're dead.

17:14.521 --> 17:15.746
JOE: There he is,

17:15.747 --> 17:17.448
my favorite flunky.

17:18.842 --> 17:21.844
There he is, my new pinhead boss.

17:21.845 --> 17:23.612
What's up, Joe?

17:23.613 --> 17:25.214
- I got an announcement, okay?
- Okay.

17:25.214 --> 17:27.082
I'm quitting our car business.

17:27.083 --> 17:29.501
Come on. I bust your balls
a little bit yesterday,

17:29.502 --> 17:30.519
now you want to quit?

17:30.520 --> 17:31.854
What are you, a snowflake?

17:31.855 --> 17:34.089
I always knew you were a flake, but...

17:34.090 --> 17:36.625
not a snowflake. Come on.

17:36.626 --> 17:39.061
I'm not quitting because of
your pathetic little jokes,

17:39.062 --> 17:41.296
you egomaniac.

17:41.297 --> 17:43.766
I'm just sick of this boss stuff.

17:43.767 --> 17:46.535
Well, kind of goes with
the satin jacket, Joe.

17:46.536 --> 17:49.204
Look, I don't want to
deal with tax documents

17:49.205 --> 17:52.274
and websites and all
that other crap, okay?

17:52.275 --> 17:54.143
I just want to work on cars.

17:54.144 --> 17:57.146
(SIGHS) Look, you might
not believe this, Baxter,

17:57.147 --> 17:59.815
but I don't... I don't
have a lot of friends.

18:00.884 --> 18:03.218
I'll take your word for it.

18:03.219 --> 18:05.554
I'm just uncomfortable
around people, okay?

18:05.555 --> 18:08.390
When a car's around, somehow,
it-it's easier for me.

18:08.391 --> 18:10.626
It's a-actually fun, you know?

18:10.627 --> 18:13.262
Look, I know that probably
sounds weird to you.

18:13.263 --> 18:14.663
No.

18:14.664 --> 18:16.932
That doesn't sound weird to me.

18:16.933 --> 18:18.500
I mean, being boss just takes

18:18.501 --> 18:20.602
- all the fun out of it.
- Yeah.

18:20.603 --> 18:22.004
That's why I didn't want to do it.

18:22.005 --> 18:24.907
I know Larabee feels the same, too.

18:24.908 --> 18:26.809
So who's gonna be the boss?

18:28.344 --> 18:29.812
Vanessa.

18:30.980 --> 18:32.014
W...

18:32.015 --> 18:33.448
I got an idea.

18:33.449 --> 18:35.450
I got a good idea.

18:36.653 --> 18:38.086
Excuse me for a minute.

18:38.087 --> 18:39.755
- Ed. Ed, listen, um...
- Yeah?

18:39.756 --> 18:41.523
... what do you know about cars?

18:41.524 --> 18:45.294
I know how to buy a
new one when they break.

18:45.295 --> 18:48.130
Okay. I'd like to nominate Ed

18:48.131 --> 18:49.932
to be the boss of our new endeavor.

18:49.933 --> 18:51.667
- Oh. Hell yeah.
- No, no, no.

18:51.668 --> 18:53.101
- That's a great idea.
- No.

18:53.102 --> 18:55.504
No, no, no, no. I don't
know anything about engines.

18:55.505 --> 18:56.805
No, no, no.

18:56.806 --> 18:59.641
You don't have to know
anything about engines.

18:59.642 --> 19:03.612
You said that being a boss is a...

19:03.613 --> 19:05.013
- heady cocktail, right?
- Yeah.

19:05.014 --> 19:07.015
Well, how would you like to be...

19:07.016 --> 19:09.952
our bartender?

19:10.954 --> 19:13.555
- I accept your nomination.
- Ah.

19:13.556 --> 19:16.358
All right. Prepare to be over-served.

19:18.194 --> 19:21.663
Well, all those in favor of Ed
being our new boss say "aye".

19:21.664 --> 19:23.065
- Oh. Aye, man.
- Aye.

19:23.066 --> 19:25.467
- It's unanimous. You're the skipper.
- All right. Good.

19:25.468 --> 19:27.502
- And you're gonna need this.
- ED: Oh.

19:30.006 --> 19:32.741
(LAUGHS) I'm humbled by
your faith in me, gentlemen.

19:32.742 --> 19:34.343
All right, first order of business,

19:34.344 --> 19:36.011
pain in the ass flows one way:

19:36.012 --> 19:37.179
from me to you.

19:37.180 --> 19:39.706
All right? All right.

19:39.707 --> 19:42.050
Now that that's settled, uh,
you'll excuse me, gentlemen.

19:42.051 --> 19:45.053
I'm on my way to create a
new folder on my desktop.

19:45.054 --> 19:46.321
I'm gonna need that back

19:46.322 --> 19:49.057
on Easter and my mom's birthday.

19:49.058 --> 19:51.827
I got some cop buddies to
let us into the impound lot.

19:51.828 --> 19:53.896
Let's go down there
and check out the cars.

19:53.897 --> 19:54.930
- Sounds like fun.
- CHUCK: Mm.

19:54.931 --> 19:56.531
I don't like that impound lot.

19:56.532 --> 19:58.367
They got too many dogs there.

19:58.368 --> 20:00.202
Well, Joe smells like cats.

20:00.203 --> 20:02.205
He goes in first.

20:09.567 --> 20:11.402
Hey, Mike Baxter here for Outdoor Man.

20:11.403 --> 20:14.505
Talking about the
importance of friendship.

20:14.506 --> 20:16.507
Maybe it doesn't come easily for you.

20:16.508 --> 20:18.575
Maybe you're shy or awkward

20:18.576 --> 20:22.513
or you're like me and you
really just don't like people.

20:22.514 --> 20:25.573
Okay, what you need to
do is find common ground

20:25.574 --> 20:27.351
that makes other folks bearable.

20:27.352 --> 20:30.921
FDR and Uncle Joe Stalin
didn't have much to talk about

20:30.922 --> 20:33.322
at the 1945 Yalta Conference.

20:33.323 --> 20:35.324
You see, one of 'em liked martinis.

20:35.325 --> 20:38.727
The other preferred Molotov cocktails.

20:38.728 --> 20:40.729
Until Frankie realized,

20:40.730 --> 20:43.232
"Hey, Joey, you like stealing property.

20:43.233 --> 20:46.335
I like taxes.

20:46.336 --> 20:49.171
We're both commie bastards!"

20:50.574 --> 20:52.908
The New Kids on the Block
had their differences,

20:52.909 --> 20:54.844
but they were always
able to put 'em aside,

20:54.845 --> 20:57.079
come together in a studio and record

20:57.080 --> 21:00.349
some of the worst
songs in music history.

21:01.718 --> 21:04.720
Yeah, we may have more that
divides us than unites us,

21:04.721 --> 21:07.356
but, luckily, it only takes
one thing to draw us together.

21:07.357 --> 21:09.258
Now, I understand... believe me...

21:09.259 --> 21:11.360
how hard it can be
sharing something you love

21:11.361 --> 21:13.596
with someone you don't.

21:13.597 --> 21:17.933
I do it every April 15.

21:19.903 --> 21:21.370
(MOUTHS)

21:23.240 --> 21:26.408
But unlike having your
hard-earned money confiscated,

21:26.409 --> 21:29.645
forging friendships can
actually help you live longer.

21:29.646 --> 21:32.243
And if my motivation is
keeping those bastards

21:32.244 --> 21:33.582
from collecting their death tax,

21:33.583 --> 21:35.389
hell, I might just live forever.

21:35.390 --> 21:37.386
Baxter out.

